<p>So as per title, I'm using the <code>X-UA-Compatible</code> meta tag to force standards mode in the current IE version. (HTML below)</p>  <p>Despite this, in IE9 it goes into compatibility mode on percentage of users machines. I use Mac and it works fine on a Win7 IE9 virtual machine and also on my Windows machine's IE9. But when I test on a colleague's laptop it goes straight into compatibility view.</p>  <p>I've tried the following meta tags, without luck:</p>  <ul> <li><code>&lt;meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=9; IE=8; IE=7"&gt;</code></li> <li><code>&lt;meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge" /&gt;</code></li> <li><code>&lt;meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge,chrome=1" /&gt;</code></li> </ul>  <p>I have tried resetting internet explorer settings using <a href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/22722381/ie9-always-runs-in-ie7-compatibility-mode">this answer</a> to the same question and it still doesn't work.</p>  <pre class="lang-html prettyprint-override"><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt; &lt;!--[if lt IE 7]&gt;      &lt;html class="no-js lt-ie9 lt-ie8 lt-ie7"&gt; &lt;![endif]--&gt; &lt;!--[if IE 7]&gt;         &lt;html class="no-js lt-ie9 lt-ie8"&gt; &lt;![endif]--&gt; &lt;!--[if IE 8]&gt;         &lt;html class="no-js lt-ie9"&gt; &lt;![endif]--&gt; &lt;!--[if gt IE 8]&gt;&lt;!--&gt; &lt;html class="no-js"&gt; &lt;!--&lt;![endif]--&gt;     &lt;head&gt;         &lt;meta charset="utf-8"&gt;         &lt;meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=9; IE=8; IE=7"&gt;         &lt;title&gt;Site&lt;/title&gt;         &lt;meta name="description" content=""&gt;         &lt;meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1"&gt; ... </code></pre>